'''Harry James Stephens''' (c. 1866 <U+2013> 25 August 1947) was an Australian journalist with a long career, mostly in Victoria and New South Wales agricultural districts. He was with ''[[The Farmer & Settler]]'' of Sydney for fourteen years and while editing that paper created Australia's first Country Party; later was editor of rival newspaper ''[[The Land (newspaper)|The Land]]''.

==History==
He was successively editor of the Melbourne ''[[The War Cry|War Cry]]'' and reporter for the Launceston ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', then founder and editor of the Launceston ''[[Federalist]]''; editor of the [[Charlton, Victoria|Charlton]] ''Tribune''; managing editor of the [[Numurkah]] ''Leader''; sub-editor of Sydney's ''[[Sunday Times]]''; editor of ''[[The Farmer & Settler]]'', Sydney 1906<U+2013>1920, in 1912, with decentralisation, rural development and defence its primary concerns.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article127694704 |title=That Alleged Country Party |newspaper=[[The_Richmond_River_Herald_and_Northern_Districts_Advertiser|The Richmond River Herald and Northern Districts Advertiser (NSW : 1886 - 1942)]] |location=NSW |date=4 July 1913 |accessdate=16 April 2015 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article117797308 |title=The Country Party |newspaper=[[The_Leader_(Orange,_NSW)|Leader (Orange, NSW : 1912 - 1922)]] |location=Orange, NSW |date=7 December 1912 |accessdate=16 April 2015 |page=8 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>; proprietor and editor of the Ouyen ''Mail''; founder and managing editor of the ''[[Sunraysia Daily]]'', Mildura;<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article74797078 |title=The "Sunraysia Daily" Editor. |newspaper=[[The Mildura Cultivator |The Mildura Cultivator (Vic. : 1888 - 1920)]] |location=Vic. |date=7 July 1920 |accessdate=16 April 2015 |page=14 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> proprietor of the ''[[Western Advertiser]]'' of [[Wentworth, New South Wales|Wentworth]];<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article124819828 |title=Mr. Harry J. Stephens |newspaper=[[Murray Pioneer and Australian River Record |Murray Pioneer and Australian River Record (Renmark, SA : 1913 - 1942)]] |location=Renmark, SA |date=2 December 1921 |accessdate=16 April 2015 |page=24 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}
</ref> publicity officer for the [[National Party]] in Sydney; editor of ''The Land'',<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article109451522 |title=Personal |newspaper=[[Murray Pioneer and Australian River Record |Murray Pioneer and Australian River Record (Renmark, SA : 1913 - 1942)]] |location=Renmark, SA |date=12 December 1930 |accessdate=16 April 2015 |page=12 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> and ''Fruit Culture''.

His last appointment was as executive of the A.B.C.'s Publicity Department.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article110547342 |title=Death of Journalist Harry J. Stephens. |newspaper=[[The Times and Northern Advertiser, Peterborough, South Australia |The Times and Northern Advertiser, Peterborough, South Australia (SA : 1919 - 1950)]] |location=SA |date=12 September 1947 |accessdate=16 April 2015 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

